1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,528
Air quality differs from place to place and day to day.

2
00:00:06,528 --> 00:00:23,741
But about 99 percent of the world’s population breathes air at some point that does not meet pollution guidelines set by the World Health Organization (WHO).

3
00:00:23,741 --> 00:00:34,144
Different forms of air pollution kill about 7 million people each year, the U.N. health agency estimates.

4
00:00:34,144 --> 00:00:46,907
But health experts say there are some actions individuals can take to protect themselves, even in the world’s most polluted cities.

5
00:00:46,907 --> 00:01:00,000
The first step is to start with the understanding that air is not only polluted when it looks smoky or smoggy, said Tanushree Ganguly.

6
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:08,885
She is an air quality expert with the Energy Policy Institute of Chicago’s India program.

7
00:01:08,885 --> 00:01:16,371
“Blue skies can’t guarantee you clean air,” Ganguly told The Associated Press.

8
00:01:16,371 --> 00:01:22,472
Air pollutants often come from people burning things.

9
00:01:22,472 --> 00:01:31,853
Examples include fuels as well as clearing operations involving crops or trees.

10
00:01:31,853 --> 00:01:37,413
Pollutants can also be released from wildfires.

11
00:01:37,413 --> 00:01:45,664
Among the most dangerous particles we can breathe in are called particulate matter.

12
00:01:45,664 --> 00:01:51,808
The smallest of these are known as PM 2.5.

13
00:01:51,808 --> 00:01:59,179
This is because they are less than 2.5 microns in diameter.

14
00:01:59,179 --> 00:02:09,515
These particles can travel deep inside human lungs and are mostly created by burning fuels.

15
00:02:09,515 --> 00:02:21,821
Larger particles, known as PM 10, are linked to agriculture, roadways, mining or wind-blown dust.

16
00:02:21,821 --> 00:02:35,731
Other dangerous pollutants include gases like nitrogen dioxide or sulfur dioxide, which are also produced from burning fuels.

17
00:02:35,731 --> 00:02:48,680
This information comes from Anumita Roychowdhury, an air pollution expert at the Center for Science and Environment in New Delhi.

18
00:02:48,680 --> 00:03:02,480
The American-based Health Effects Institute says air pollution is the second-largest risk factor for early death worldwide, behind high blood pressure.

19
00:03:02,480 --> 00:03:18,021
Short-term exposure can cause asthma attacks and increase the risk of heart attacks and stroke, especially in older people and those with existing medical problems.

20
00:03:18,021 --> 00:03:26,008
Long-term exposure can cause serious heart and lung problems that can lead to death.

21
00:03:26,008 --> 00:03:41,344
A recent study by the U.N. children’s agency UNICEF found that more than 500 million children in East Asia and Pacific countries breathe unhealthy air.

22
00:03:41,344 --> 00:03:49,869
The pollution is linked to the deaths of 100 children under age 5 every day.

23
00:03:49,869 --> 00:04:03,205
June Kunugi, UNICEF’s Regional Director for East Asia, said the polluted air limits growth, harms lungs and affects thinking abilities.

24
00:04:03,205 --> 00:04:11,483
“Every breath matters, but for too many children every breath can bring harm,” she said.

25
00:04:11,483 --> 00:04:22,624
Over 6,000 cities in 117 countries now record and follow air quality levels.

26
00:04:22,624 --> 00:04:28,507
Many mobile apps include air quality information as well.

27
00:04:28,507 --> 00:04:36,824
But it can be difficult to know how bad the air is by looking at these numbers.

28
00:04:36,824 --> 00:04:50,168
To help people better understand air quality levels, many countries have established an air quality index, or AQI.

29
00:04:50,168 --> 00:04:56,027
Larger numbers on this index mean worse air.

30
00:04:56,027 --> 00:05:02,251
Different countries have different air quality standards.

31
00:05:02,251 --> 00:05:20,355
For example, India’s daily PM 2.5 limit is more than 1.5 times higher than in Thailand and 4 times higher than WHO standards.

32
00:05:20,355 --> 00:05:33,1000
For individuals, experts say the goal should be to limit exposure when air quality is bad, by staying indoors or wearing a mask.

33
00:05:33,1000 --> 00:05:37,277
This is not always possible, though.

34
00:05:37,277 --> 00:05:41,832
Danny Djarum is with the World Resources Institute.

35
00:05:41,832 --> 00:05:51,931
He told the AP there are many people who live or work outside and “can’t really afford” to stay indoors.

36
00:05:51,931 --> 00:06:04,085
People also need to watch indoor air pollution that can be caused by common household activities like cooking or burning incense.

37
00:06:04,085 --> 00:06:13,576
While air purifiers can help reduce indoor air pollution, experts say they do have limitations.

38
00:06:13,576 --> 00:06:23,099
The devices work by pulling air from a room and then pushing it through a filter that traps pollutants.

39
00:06:23,099 --> 00:06:27,464
The filtered air is then sent back into the room.

40
00:06:27,464 --> 00:06:35,245
Air purifiers work best when used in small spaces and when people are nearby.

41
00:06:35,245 --> 00:06:47,851
This is because they can only clean a certain amount of air, said Rajasekhar Balasubramanian of the National University of Singapore.

42
00:06:47,851 --> 00:06:55,819
He added, “If we have a tiny air purifier in a large room, it won’t be effective.”

43
00:06:55,819 --> 00:06:58,325
I’m John Russell.

44
00:06:58,325 --> 00:07:00,605
And I'm Caty Weaver.